<ue5><m0>Buried cocaine stash allegedly<ql>
linked to arrested Outlaws leader<ql>
<m1><ue5><ep>
<m0>    <m0>TORONTO<m0> (--) Police say they have found a stash of buried cocaine on a farm near Niagara Falls that is allegedly linked to an Outlaws Motorcycle Club leader.<ep>
   Sgt. Mark Carter said officers seized the drugs on the farm that is apparently home to Mario Parente, president of the St. Catharines Outlaws. He was arrested Monday.<ep>
   Parente was charged with drug trafficking and threatening death. He remains in custody pending the outcome of his bail hearing, which is scheduled to resume Monday in Hamilton.<ql>
<m1><ql>
<styl>rdup,17p8<ql>
<ue5><m0>Manitoba meets some of guards'<ql>
safety concerns after jail riot<ql>
<m1><ue5><ep>
<m0>   <m0>WINNIPEG<m0> (--) Officials on Saturday met some of the demands of guards who threatened to stay away from work at Headingley jail because of safety concerns at the riot-torn prison.<ep>
   The Manitoba government will install a million-dollar electromagnetic locking system to replace one master key that was used to open cells and barriers in many different areas of the burned-out jail.<ep>
   And range bars dividing large parts of the jail won't be removed at the Depression-era building, the scene of a bloody rampage last week.<ep>
   Guards say it's a start but not enough. They still want a full public inquiry and the resignation of senior justice officials. They said they still might walk off the job.<ql>
<m1><ql>
<styl>rdup,17p8<ql>
<ue5><m0>Samples of hay fever drug<ql>
believed diluted, then sold<ql>
<m1><ue5><ep>
<m0>   <m0>TORONTO<m0> (--) An investigation has been launched into how at least 160 physician samples of a prescription allergy medicine ended up diluted and on sale in pharmacies.<ep>
   Thousands of bottles of Rhinalar, manufactured by Hoffman-LaRoche Ltd. in Mississauga, Ontario, were recalled last week after two consumers complained the treatment for hay fever wasn't working.<ep>
   Lorenzo Biondi, a spokesman for the company, said tests by the federal Health Protection Branch found no evidence of any illicit drugs or known poisons in the medicine. ``It could just be water,'' he said.<ep>
   So far, the company has found 160 bottles that have been tampered with, he said.<ql>
